{
  "texts": [
    "Bradford's Law, which explains the unequal distribution of journal articles across research fields, is widely referenced in bibliometrics, yet its origins are subject to debate.",
    "Samuel C. Bradford first introduced this principle in 1934, but some scholars argue that its conceptual roots may predate Bradford's work, connecting it to early ideas in the distribution of information.",
    "Despite this uncertainty, the law's practical application in determining core journals for specific subjects remains unquestioned [31].",
    "Moreover, Bradford's Law can be seen as a specific instance of the Pareto distribution.",
    "Just as the Pareto principle suggests that 80% of outcomes are derived from 20% of causes, Bradford's Law similarly highlights that a small proportion of journals account for a large share of important research articles."
  ]
}